1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,960
Now once we have a single block,

2

00:00:01,960  -->  00:00:04,880
it's time to implement our transformer model.

3

00:00:04,880  -->  00:00:09,980
To do this, we will again define a new class that inherits from the module type,

4

00:00:09,980  -->  00:00:11,380
and to implement it,

5

00:00:11,380  -->  00:00:14,620
we use all the types we've previously defined.

6

00:00:14,620  -->  00:00:18,820
We'll start implementing this class with defining its building blocks.

7

00:00:18,820  -->  00:00:21,720
If we recall to use our transformer model,

8

00:00:21,720  -->  00:00:25,865
we first need to convert input token IDs into embedding vectors.

9

00:00:25,865  -->  00:00:28,880
To do this, we'll use this embedding type.

10

00:00:28,880  -->  00:00:33,900
This type will map each token ID to its own embedding vector.

11

00:00:33,900  -->  00:00:38,000
The first parameter here is the number of embedding vectors,

12

00:00:38,000  -->  00:00:42,280
which is the number of token IDs we have in our vocabulary.

13

00:00:42,280  -->  00:00:46,720
The second parameter is dimensionality of embedding vectors.

14

00:00:46,720  -->  00:00:50,100
We also need to implement the positional encoding that

15

00:00:50,100  -->  00:00:54,640
produces embedding vectors for each position in the context window.

16

00:00:54,640  -->  00:00:57,980
For this, we'll use the embedding type as well.

17

00:00:57,980  -->  00:01:01,780
But the number of vectors in the stable is different.

18

00:01:01,780  -->  00:01:06,600
We need a different vector for each position of the context window

19

00:01:06,600  -->  00:01:11,540
so we pass the context size here for the number of vectors in this table.

20

00:01:11,540  -->  00:01:17,320
We then create blocks for our model one by one and then combine them in the sequence.

21

00:01:17,320  -->  00:01:21,240
This will allow us to apply these blocks one after the other.

22

00:01:21,240  -->  00:01:24,200
We also add a final layer normalization,

23

00:01:24,200  -->  00:01:27,320
and we also need to add one more component.

24

00:01:27,320  -->  00:01:32,340
Remember that the output of each block consists of embedding vectors,

25

00:01:32,340  -->  00:01:37,805
but we need to convert these vectors into predictions for token IDs.

26

00:01:37,805  -->  00:01:43,180
To do this, we will add a linear layer that converts an embedding vector in

27

00:01:43,180  -->  00:01:48,980
every position into prediction scores for what token ID should be generated.

28

00:01:48,980  -->  00:01:51,300
We will pass the vocabulary size here,

29

00:01:51,300  -->  00:01:56,060
since we need a prediction score for each of the token IDs in our vocabulary.

30

00:01:56,060  -->  00:01:59,020
Now we need to implement the forward method,

31

00:01:59,020  -->  00:02:02,240
and we first convert all token IDs into

32

00:02:02,240  -->  00:02:05,640
embedding vectors and compute the positional encoding.

33

00:02:05,640  -->  00:02:11,720
To compute it, we create a sequence of numbers from zero to the number of input tokens,

34

00:02:11,720  -->  00:02:14,775
and then we pass it to this embedding layer.

35

00:02:14,775  -->  00:02:18,910
We then add positional encoding to the embedding vectors.

36

00:02:18,910  -->  00:02:20,510
To generate this sequence,

37

00:02:20,510  -->  00:02:24,590
we need to get the number of input tokens from the input shape.

38

00:02:24,590  -->  00:02:28,090
We then apply each transformer block one by one,

39

00:02:28,090  -->  00:02:30,230
then we apply the normalization,

40

00:02:30,230  -->  00:02:33,010
and finally, we convert embedding vectors into

41

00:02:33,010  -->  00:02:36,570
logits for every position in the context window.

42

00:02:36,570  -->  00:02:42,675
Now to test it, let's initialize our DemoGBT model using our configuration.

43

00:02:42,675  -->  00:02:47,420
I will also move this model to GPU if it is available.

44

00:02:47,420  -->  00:02:48,880
To test our model,

45

00:02:48,880  -->  00:02:53,900
we encode a test phrase using our tokenizer and pass it to our model.

46

00:02:53,900  -->  00:02:59,740
We need to use the unsqueeze method to add an extra dimension to our vector.

47

00:02:59,740  -->  00:03:04,580
This is because the encode method returns a one dimensional tensor,

48

00:03:04,580  -->  00:03:07,800
but our model expects a patch of inputs,

49

00:03:07,800  -->  00:03:11,640
so we need to convert it into a two dimensional tensor,

50

00:03:11,640  -->  00:03:15,720
and the output from our model will have the following shape.

51

00:03:15,720  -->  00:03:18,780
In our case, the input had one sequence,

52

00:03:18,780  -->  00:03:21,550
so we have a patch of Size 1.

53

00:03:21,550  -->  00:03:26,680
This dimension is equal two because our input had two input tokens.

54

00:03:26,680  -->  00:03:29,300
For every position, for this input phrase,

55

00:03:29,300  -->  00:03:33,520
our model returned predictions for the next token ID,

56

00:03:33,520  -->  00:03:38,240
and it gave prediction scores for every token in our vocabulary.

57

00:03:38,240  -->  00:03:42,600
To rub this up, we need to define two more helper functions.

58

00:03:42,600  -->  00:03:49,180
I'll first add a function called generate to create torch sequences using our model.

59

00:03:49,180  -->  00:03:51,880
This function will receive a model to use,

60

00:03:51,880  -->  00:03:57,460
a prompt converted to token IDs and the max number of tokens to generate.

61

00:03:57,460  -->  00:03:58,960
What we'll do in this function,

62

00:03:58,960  -->  00:04:02,620
we first initialize the output with the prompt IDs,

63

00:04:02,620  -->  00:04:04,820
and on every iteration,

64

00:04:04,820  -->  00:04:10,360
we pass the output we generated so far to our model to generate the next token.

65

00:04:10,360  -->  00:04:13,255
We then get the logits from our model.

66

00:04:13,255  -->  00:04:17,930
But we're only interested in logits in the latest position,

67

00:04:17,930  -->  00:04:19,870
since this is the prediction for

68

00:04:19,870  -->  00:04:23,510
the token that should be generated after the given prompt.

69

00:04:23,510  -->  00:04:25,710
We only get these logits.

70

00:04:25,710  -->  00:04:28,190
We then take these logits and we use

71

00:04:28,190  -->  00:04:32,730
the softmax function to convert logits to probabilities.

72

00:04:32,730  -->  00:04:34,770
You might think that at this stage,

73

00:04:34,770  -->  00:04:38,075
we should get a token with the highest probability.

74

00:04:38,075  -->  00:04:43,030
But it will lead to generating repetitive and boring outputs.

75

00:04:43,030  -->  00:04:48,290
Instead, we sample the next token based on these probabilities,

76

00:04:48,290  -->  00:04:52,490
instead of always taking the token with the highest probability.

77

00:04:52,490  -->  00:04:55,950
This will generate a more interesting output,

78

00:04:55,950  -->  00:05:01,690
and we will explore this aspect of LLMs in more details in some later videos.

79

00:05:01,690  -->  00:05:04,090
Now, once we have the next token ID,

80

00:05:04,090  -->  00:05:06,330
we add it to the output phrase,

81

00:05:06,330  -->  00:05:08,810
and then we repeat this process.

82

00:05:08,810  -->  00:05:11,755
Finally, we'll add another helper function.

83

00:05:11,755  -->  00:05:15,260
This function will be called generate with prompt,

84

00:05:15,260  -->  00:05:19,500
which will be a higher level of wrapper for the generate function.

85

00:05:19,500  -->  00:05:21,180
It takes a prompt string,

86

00:05:21,180  -->  00:05:24,920
and it encodes it using the tokenizer into token IDs.

87

00:05:24,920  -->  00:05:27,380
It then takes this encoded prompt,

88

00:05:27,380  -->  00:05:30,620
passes it with the model to the generate function,

89

00:05:30,620  -->  00:05:34,780
and decode the result token IDs into a string.

90

00:05:34,780  -->  00:05:40,380
We also call the eval method on our model to switch it into the inference mode.

91

00:05:40,380  -->  00:05:43,700
Now, let's test our generate with prom function and

92

00:05:43,700  -->  00:05:49,160
our transformer model and pass this prompt with the tokenizer and the model,

93

00:05:49,160  -->  00:05:50,785
and see what we'll get.

94

00:05:50,785  -->  00:05:53,100
As you can see, this function has worked.

95

00:05:53,100  -->  00:05:57,150
We have the prompt at the beginning of the generated output.

96

00:05:57,150  -->  00:06:01,230
But the remaining of the output is complete gibberish.

97

00:06:01,230  -->  00:06:04,510
This is because we have not trained our model yet,

98

00:06:04,510  -->  00:06:07,790
and this is exactly what we will do next.
